By Week 46 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern was no longer subtle. Power was being used less as a public trust and more as a private instrument, and the week\'92s events showed three strands tightening together: law as a shield for insiders and a weapon against opponents, citizenship and safety sorted by origin and loyalty, and force\'97military and police\'97turned outward on the vulnerable and downward on dissent. The Democracy Clock stayed at 8:11 p.m. in public terms, but the internal movement told a different story. The system registered another small step toward danger, not because of one dramatic break, but because many smaller moves all pointed the same way. The week\'92s theme was consolidation. Practices that had appeared as shocks earlier in the term were now being repeated, normalized, and built into the machinery of government.\
\
At the start of Week 46, the Clock stood at 8:11 p.m., already deep into the evening of democratic risk. By the end, it still read 8:11 p.m., but the underlying measure had slipped by a tenth of a minute. That fractional change reflects how the week\'92s damage was structural rather than spectacular. The president\'92s use of pardons and commutations to free corrupt allies and a convicted foreign drug trafficker, the Justice Department\'92s quiet removal of protections for LGBTQ+ prisoners, and the expansion of nationality-based immigration bans all pushed the traits \'93law is a weapon, not a limit\'94 and \'93citizenship stratified by heritage\'94 further into the red. At the same time, courts and Congress did not stand still. Judges struck down illegal U.S. attorney appointments and blocked warrantless immigration arrests in Washington, and lawmakers opened inquiries into alleged war crimes at sea. Those acts of resistance helped keep the clock from lurching forward, but they did not reverse the deeper trend. The week\'92s net effect was a slow tightening of an already constricting system.\
\
The first major development was the open use of clemency and legal process to protect elites and punish enemies. Over a few days, the president pardoned former Honduran president Juan Orlando Hern\'e1ndez, convicted of building a \'93cocaine superhighway\'94 to the United States, commuted the sentence of David Gentile, who had defrauded thousands of investors in a $1.6 billion scheme, and granted clemency to Representative Henry Cuellar, under indictment for a $600,000 foreign bribery scheme. He also pardoned Tim Leiweke, an entertainment executive accused of rigging a public university arena bid. These were not isolated acts of mercy. They came in the context of more than 2,000 pardons and commutations issued in 2025, many for politically connected or wealthy figures. The winners were clear: corrupt officials, financiers, and foreign strongmen with ties to the president. The losers were the ordinary defendants who could not hope for such favor, and the public\'92s belief that law applies equally. The trait \'93financial crimes by elites are unpunished or quietly settled\'94 jumped sharply, because the signal to insiders was unmistakable. Proximity to power could erase even the gravest convictions.\
\
Alongside these pardons, the administration moved to reshape the legal landscape itself. The president claimed that all documents signed by Joe Biden using an autopen\'97including pardons and executive orders\'97were invalid, and that he could \'93terminate\'94 them. There is no constitutional basis for such a claim, and courts and scholars have long accepted autopen signatures as valid. The assertion mattered less as a legal argument than as a political one. It suggested that a sitting president could unilaterally void his predecessor\'92s lawful acts, including grants of mercy and regulatory decisions, by fiat. At the same time, the Justice Department\'92s second-in-command, Todd Blanche, warned corporate lawyers that those who publicly criticized the administration\'92s white-collar enforcement approach might find their clients treated less leniently. Together, these moves deepened the sense that law was being bent to serve the regime\'92s friends and threaten its critics. The trait \'93law is a weapon, not a limit\'94 edged higher, not because statutes had changed, but because their application had become more openly contingent on loyalty.\
\
The second development was a decisive turn toward heritage-based stratification of citizenship and legal status. The president used social media to threaten denaturalization of certain immigrants and to call for a \'93purge\'94 of those he deemed undesirable. He singled out Somali immigrants as \'93garbage\'94 and tied an individual crime by an Afghan national to broad claims about Afghan and Somali communities. Stephen Miller, a long-time policy architect, argued in public that Afghan immigrants should be judged as a group, not as individuals, because they supposedly carry their home country\'92s conditions with them. These words were not mere rhetoric. They were paired with sweeping policy changes: a pause on all pending asylum decisions at U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services, affecting roughly 1.5 million cases; an indefinite halt to Afghan immigration processing; and an \'93adjudicative hold\'94 on all applications from 19 \'93high-risk\'94 countries, including Afghanistan, Burma, Iran, and Venezuela.\
\
The USCIS memo went further, ordering a re-review of immigration benefits already granted since January 20, 2021, to people from those 19 countries. That meant green cards, work authorizations, and even naturalization approvals could be reopened and questioned, not because of new individual evidence, but because of a change in political judgment about entire nationalities. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem then announced plans to expand the travel ban to more than 30 countries, again on a nationality basis. The Department of Veterans Affairs created a new database of non-citizen workers and affiliates, to be shared with other agencies for immigration enforcement. In Minneapolis and New Orleans, ICE deployed strike teams and hundreds of agents to target Somali and Latino communities, with reports of racial profiling and even the mistaken pursuit of a U.S. citizen. In Boston, ICE deported a 19-year-old student to Honduras less than 48 hours after arrest, despite a federal judge\'92s emergency order barring her removal for 72 hours. These actions collectively shifted the trait \'93citizenship stratified by wealth, ideology, and heritage\'94 upward. Legal status, once anchored in statutes and individual facts, was now subject to sweeping group-based suspicion and, at times, open defiance of court orders.\
