A third development lay in the normalization of extrajudicial force at sea and the militarization of domestic security. On September 2, the U.S. military had struck a small boat in the Caribbean, killing nine of eleven people aboard. Video shown to senators in Week 46 revealed that two survivors clung to the wreckage for more than forty minutes before a second strike killed them. Reports indicated that Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth had ordered that there be \'93no survivors,\'94 and that Admiral Frank Bradley had relayed and executed that order. Legal experts, including a working group of former Judge Advocate General officers, stated that if true, the order and second strike would constitute war crimes under the Geneva Conventions and the War Crimes Act, which protect shipwrecked individuals \'93hors de combat.\'94 Yet the White House press secretary defended the legality of the second strike without providing evidence, and Hegseth himself, in a cabinet meeting, praised a campaign of sinking \'93narco boats\'94 that had already killed at least 87 people in more than twenty strikes.\
