Congress did respond. The Senate and House Armed Services Committees opened inquiries, requested video and audio of the strikes, and held classified briefings with Admiral Bradley and the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs. Lawmakers from both parties expressed deep concern, and former military lawyers called for prosecution if the facts were confirmed. But even as oversight began, U.S. Southern Command confirmed a new lethal strike in the eastern Pacific, killing four more men on a boat alleged to be operated by a designated terrorist organization. The Pentagon\'92s inspector general released a report finding that Hegseth had also shared secret war plans over an unapproved Signal chat, risking operational security. The trait \'93police and military aligned with elite preservation, not public defense\'94 moved higher, because the pattern was not of a single rogue operation corrected by institutions, but of a sustained campaign justified as a \'93war\'94 on drug traffickers, with legal authority stretched and civilian oversight struggling to catch up.\
\
The militarization of domestic space followed a similar logic. After an ambush that killed a National Guard member near the White House, the Pentagon armed all Guard soldiers deployed in Washington, D.C., with live weapons and ordered them to conduct joint patrols with local police. An additional 500 troops were sent to the city. This was framed as a response to an \'93urgent threat\'94 to American cities, but raised questions about training, rules of engagement, and the line between military and civilian policing. In California, a federal judge questioned why the administration continued to exercise federal control over the California National Guard months after protests had subsided, but had not yet ruled on the state\'92s request to regain command. In Florida, appellate judges blocked the closure of the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 immigration facility, known for harsh conditions and alleged human rights abuses, allowing it to keep operating under state emergency management rather than federal oversight. These decisions showed how courts could both check and entrench executive and state uses of force. The net effect was to deepen the sense that security institutions were being repurposed to project power inward, with only partial and uneven restraint.\
