A fourth development was the fusion of foreign policy, private enrichment, and foreign influence. Steve Witkoff, appointed as a special envoy for peace missions, traveled to Moscow with Jared Kushner to negotiate a \'93Trump plan\'94 for Ukraine that heavily favored Russian demands. The plan, based on a Russian-authored paper, required Ukraine to cede territory and abandon NATO aspirations, and it was developed largely outside the State Department. At the same time, Witkoff maintained a real estate partnership with Len Blavatnik, a billionaire sanctioned by Ukraine, and his financial disclosure form remained unsigned by ethics officials and allegedly incomplete. Kushner, for his part, continued to collect substantial fees from foreign governments through his private equity firm, Affinity Partners, which had raised $4.8 billion, nearly all from foreign sources, including $2 billion from Saudi Arabia\'92s sovereign wealth fund. He participated in high-level talks with Vladimir Putin in Moscow without being formally appointed as a special government employee, raising potential Logan Act and emoluments concerns.\
