Domestically, crony capitalism showed up in more familiar forms. The administration used a \'93golden share\'94 arrangement to exert control over U.S. Steel and block the closure of an Illinois plant, demonstrating that the government could reach into a private company\'92s decisions when it suited its political goals. The Pentagon and Commerce Department awarded a $620 million loan and additional support to Vulcan Elements, a startup producing rare-earth magnets for military use, funded by a firm where Donald Trump Jr. is a partner. The Department of Defense also received warrants giving it the right to buy a stake in the company later. At the same time, a Trump-family crypto firm, World Liberty Financial, faced potential Nasdaq delisting for failing to file required reports, had cycled through multiple chief executives, and saw a subsidiary found liable for money laundering abroad. These episodes did not just show individual conflicts. They illustrated a governing style in which public industrial policy and family-linked ventures were intertwined, and in which regulatory compliance by those ventures lagged behind their political access. The trait \'93policy driven by elite lobbying and money\'94 ticked higher, because decisions about tariffs, LNG exports, and defense loans all aligned with the interests of a small, connected group.\
