A sixth development concerned information, memory, and the management of public perception. The White House launched a new section of its official website to catalog \'93media offenders of the week,\'94 complete with an \'93Offender Hall of Shame\'94 and a searchable database of stories labeled as biased or malpractice. The Pentagon adopted press access rules that favored pro-Trump digital influencers over traditional reporters, prompting a lawsuit from the New York Times alleging violations of First and Fifth Amendment rights. The administration stopped publishing key federal economic indicators, forcing analysts and the public to rely on private data even as job cuts mounted and private-sector employment fell by 32,000 in November. At the same time, the Justice Department and Congress moved toward unprecedented transparency in one narrow area: the Epstein files. A federal judge in Florida ordered the release of grand jury transcripts from the 2006\'962007 Epstein investigation under a new Epstein Files Transparency Act, and lawmakers from both parties pressed Attorney General Pam Bondi for a briefing on new materials. House Democrats released photos and videos from Epstein\'92s private island to keep pressure on the Justice Department ahead of a records deadline.\
