The seventh development involved the courts, which both resisted and enabled the erosion of democratic norms. On one side, federal judges in Virginia and New Jersey ruled that the administration\'92s appointments of U.S. attorneys Lindsey Halligan and Alina Habba were unlawful, leading to the dismissal of politically charged cases against James Comey and Letitia James and reinforcing the requirement of Senate confirmation. A federal judge in Washington, D.C., blocked widespread immigration arrests without warrants or probable cause, requiring agents to document specific facts and share them with plaintiffs\'92 attorneys. Courts in Alabama and New Orleans intervened to protect Black voting rights and to scrutinize a large clergy abuse settlement, respectively. On the other side, the Supreme Court approved a Texas congressional map that added up to five Republican-leaning districts and had been found racially gerrymandered by a lower court, and agreed to hear a case on the president\'92s order restricting birthright citizenship. Appellate judges in Florida kept the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 detention facility open despite a closure order based on human rights concerns. These rulings pushed the traits \'93courts rule for donors and elites\'94 and \'93judicial independence eroded by politicized appointments\'94 slightly higher, because they showed how a bench reshaped over years could now deliver outcomes that favored partisan and enforcement priorities, even as individual judges elsewhere tried to hold the line.\
