Looking ahead from Week 46, several scheduled or pending decisions loomed as tests of whether remaining institutions could still check the trajectory. The Supreme Court\'92s hearing in Trump v. Barbara would determine whether an executive order could narrow birthright citizenship, striking at the heart of the Fourteenth Amendment. Congressional investigations into the September 2 boat strikes and the broader campaign of \'93narco-boat\'94 attacks would show whether bipartisan concern could translate into real accountability for alleged war crimes by a sitting defense secretary and senior commanders. The release of Epstein grand jury materials and other files under the new transparency law would test whether the Justice Department would apply openness evenly, or use it to target some elites while shielding others. And the new hepatitis B vaccine guidance, once implemented, would reveal how hospitals and parents respond when long-standing public health norms are unsettled by politicized advisory bodies.\
\
In the larger arc of the term, Week 46 matters because it shows a regime settling into its preferred shape. The use of pardons to free corrupt allies and foreign traffickers, the expansion of travel bans and re-reviews that make legal status contingent on origin and politics, the normalization of lethal strikes on shipwrecked survivors, and the quiet removal of protections for LGBTQ+ prisoners all point in the same direction: a state that reserves mercy and safety for those close to power, and uses law and force to discipline those outside it. Courts, Congress, and civil society still act, sometimes with courage and effect, but their efforts are reactive and fragmented, often arriving after the fact. The Democracy Clock ends the week still at 8:11 p.m., but the moral floor beneath it has sunk further. The risk is not only that democracy will be lost in a single blow, but that it will be worn away by weeks like this one, where the evening grows a little darker while the clocks on the wall appear unchanged.\
